{
  "answer": "In *Manusmṛti* (Laws of Manu) Chapter 1, Manu describes the Self-Existent One's seed becoming a golden egg, from which Brahmā is born, and the subsequent splitting of that egg to form heaven and earth (verses 9 and 12–13):[^1][^2][^3]\n\n> That seed became a golden egg, in splendor like the thousand-rayed sun; in it he himself was born as Brahma, the great father of all the worlds.[^1]  \n>   \n> After dwelling in that egg for a full year, that divine Lord, by his own contemplation, split the egg in two.[^2]  \n>   \n> And with those two halves he formed the **heavens and the earth**, and between them the middle region, the eight directions, and the eternal abode of the waters.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, [p-153021](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-153021).\n[^2]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, [p-cd6713](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-cd6713).\n[^3]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, [p-3bd729](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-3bd729).",
